Climate and Community

Planning for climate change mitigation
in a Columbia Basin community

scroll or click to continue

South Eastern British Columbia

The Columbia Basin watershed is home to about 160,000 people.
Energy, carbon emissions, and climate change are important
issues of public policy with opportunities and
consequences for community planning.

Columbia Basin residents and businesses spend about $560 million yearly on the energy that fuels vehicles, operates buildings and powers machines.

Columbia Basin residents individually spend about $3,700 on these operations.

The gasoline, diesel, oil and propane burned in a Basin community generates about 7.5 tonnes
of climate changing CO2 per resident.

About 65% of CO2 emissions are attributed to the energy a community uses for travel.
About 25% are attributed to the energy a community uses to operate buildings.

All Columbia Basin communities are required to reduce emissions, and doing this could have economic benefits.

A communitys energy needs and CO2 production are significantly impacted by the
planning of land uses and design of buildings.
But how much do these choices matter?

The population of the Columbia Basin watershed has doubled since the 1970s,
and so grows the demand for fuel and the C02 emissions of residents.

Let's compare four different ways a community
could add 500 new residents

Suburban Walkability

Suburban neighbourhoods are typically residential only areas without nearby services and amenities. Nearly all household trips would be longer and typically by automobile.

Suburban Energy and Emissions

Households in the suburbs typically need more heat, power and fuel and generate more CO2 emissions per person than households living in more compact, mixed use alternatives. About 2/3 of energy used and emissions generated are travel related.

Neighbourhood Nodes Walkability

Neighbourhood Nodes Energy & Emissions

Households in energy e cient duplex, townhome and apartment buildings, located near jobs and commercial services, can reduce annual CO2 emissions by up to 50% (compared to suburban households). Much of the reduction is attributable to more compact buildings and fewer, shorter automobile trips to services.
